data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue execution | Remove — cooperative model doesn't need it |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. The entire approach must shift from **preemptive** (runtime injects exception) to **cooperative** (code checks a token).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: overload that passes the token into the work
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Token not passed to work** | The `Func<T>` overload preserves API compat but **cannot stop work that ignores the token**. The work keeps running on a thread-pool thread until it finishes. Prefer the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` not disposed** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Blocking I/O won't cancel** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive`, etc. don't check the token. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads that accept a token. |
| **`OperationCanceledException` swallowed** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`). Don't swallow it deeper in the call chain. |

### Caller Migration Example

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowComputation(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// After (.NET 8) — pass the token so cancellation actually stops work
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

The fundamental trade-off: `Thread.Abort` could kill uncooperative code (at the risk of corruption). Cooperative cancellation is safe but **only works if the work checks the token**. For truly uncooperative code (e.g., third-party libs), move the work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`.
